        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>B-roll</strong> is supplementary footage intercut with the main (A-roll) shot of a video — for example, cutaways of a product, hands on a keyboard, or environment shots that play over a voiceover. It hides edits, illustrates what the speaker is describing, and keeps pace. On short-form platforms like Reels, TikTok, and YouTube Shorts, well-cut b-roll can lift watch time and engagement by <strong>3x</strong> versus a static talking-head shot.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ideal clip length</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-8 seconds</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing · Video</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Engagement lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Up to 3x</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Nobody watches a two-minute talking-head shot without wanting to scroll. B-roll is what buys the extra 30, 60, 90 seconds of attention — the difference between a video that gets seen and one that gets skipped.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is b-roll?</h2>
        <p>B-roll is any supplementary footage used to enrich the primary shot of a video. The primary footage — a person speaking to camera, an interview, a keynote — is called <strong>A-roll</strong>. Everything you cut to while the audio continues is b-roll: product close-ups, environment shots, screen recordings, hands-on-task shots, atmospheric scenes.</p>
        <p>The term originates in film. Editors literally used two reels of film: the A-roll carried the primary scene, the B-roll carried alternative or secondary footage. The convention survived into digital editing.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Cutaway b-roll</strong> — shots that illustrate what the speaker is describing</li>
          <li><strong>Establishing b-roll</strong> — sets the scene at the start of a segment</li>
          <li><strong>Transitional b-roll</strong> — bridges two ideas or timelines</li>
          <li><strong>Editorial b-roll</strong> — covers a mistake or jump cut in the A-roll</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why editors love b-roll</div>
          <p>B-roll gives an editor freedom to cut. Without it, every stumble in the A-roll leaves a visible jump cut. With it, the editor cuts to a cutaway and the viewer never notices the interviewee's third attempt at the sentence.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why b-roll matters for marketing video</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Longer watch time.</strong> Visual variety keeps viewers watching. Platform algorithms — TikTok, Instagram, YouTube — reward retention above every other signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Better retention of the message.</strong> Cognitive science shows viewers remember information paired with matching visuals 6x better than audio alone (Brain Rules, Medina).</li>
          <li><strong>Editable A-roll.</strong> With enough b-roll, editors can fix errors, tighten pacing, and rearrange arguments without re-shooting.</li>
          <li><strong>Platform-native pacing.</strong> Reels and TikTok reward cuts every 1-3 seconds. B-roll is what makes that rhythm possible.</li>
          <li><strong>Product visualization.</strong> For SaaS, DTC, and services, b-roll is where the product actually appears — the A-roll only talks about it.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How b-roll works in a video edit</h2>
        <p>The edit follows a simple pattern: the A-roll carries the argument or story; b-roll appears on top of the audio to illustrate, reinforce, or transition.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment">// Timeline structure</span><br>
          A-roll audio: <span class="uf-label">continuous voiceover / interview</span><br>
          A-roll video: <span class="uf-label">visible for 40-60% of the runtime</span><br>
          B-roll video: <span class="uf-label">covers the remaining 40-60%, cut to 3-8 sec clips</span><br>
          Music: <span class="uf-label">low bed, ducks under speech</span><br>
          Text overlays: <span class="uf-label">reinforce the key phrase every 8-12 sec</span>
        </div>

        <h3>The 5-to-1 rule</h3>
        <p>Shoot at least 5x more b-roll than you think you need. Editors always find gaps in coverage. A 60-second final video typically requires 3-5 minutes of usable b-roll clips shot on location.</p>

        <h3>Match motion, not just topic</h3>
        <p>The best b-roll matches what the speaker says <em>and</em> the visual momentum of the previous shot. If the A-roll is a slow zoom-in on a face, cut to a slow-motion product close-up — not a fast pan. The eye reads mismatched motion as a jarring edit.</p>

        <h2 id="types">What b-roll to shoot for marketing videos</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Category</th><th>What to capture</th><th>Best use</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Product in use</strong></td><td>Hands using the product, screens showing the app</td><td>SaaS demos, DTC unboxings</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Workspace / environment</strong></td><td>Office, workshop, storefront, atmosphere</td><td>Behind-the-scenes, founder stories</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Hands-on-task close-ups</strong></td><td>Detail shots of hands working</td><td>Tutorials, service videos</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Customer interactions</strong></td><td>Customer service, delivery, use in the wild</td><td>Testimonials, brand videos</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Establishing shots</strong></td><td>Building exterior, city, landscape</td><td>Opening titles, chapter breaks</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Screen recordings</strong></td><td>App walkthroughs, data views, UI motion</td><td>Feature explainers, demos</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real b-roll examples in marketing</h2>

        <h3>1. DTC skincare — Instagram Reels</h3>
        <p>Brand tested two Reels formats over 30 days. Version A: founder talking to camera for 30 seconds. Version B: same audio, cut over product close-ups, texture shots, and hands-in-use footage every 2-3 seconds. Version B drove 3x more saves and shares. The b-roll was the format.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B consultant — LinkedIn video</h3>
        <p>A consultant switched from static webcam shots to full A-roll plus screen-recording b-roll of the actual frameworks they were describing. Reach per post went from 200 views to 2,000+. Same message, visualized.</p>

        <h3>3. Local restaurant — the counter-example</h3>
        <p>Restaurant filmed the owner explaining a new dish direct to camera. No cutaways to the dish, the kitchen, or the plating. Post reached 400 people. A competitor with a similar audience filmed 15-second reels of the plating process — hands, steam, close-ups. They built 15,000 local food-lover followers in 8 months.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">B-roll vs A-roll — how they work together</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>A-roll</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The primary shot — usually a person or narrator</li>
              <li>Carries the audio and narrative arc</li>
              <li>Establishes tone, pace, and voice</li>
              <li>Visible for 40-60% of the final runtime</li>
              <li>Example: founder talking to camera</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>B-roll</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Supplementary shots cut in on top of the A-roll audio</li>
              <li>Illustrates, reinforces, and paces the story</li>
              <li>Hides edits and adds visual variety</li>
              <li>Visible for 40-60% of the final runtime</li>
              <li>Example: hands using the product while founder speaks</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Neither works alone. A-roll without b-roll is a talking head; b-roll without A-roll is a mood video with nothing to say. The craft is the interplay.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for b-roll in marketing video</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Shoot 5x more than you think you need.</strong> Editors always run out of coverage. Abundance beats precision on the shoot day.</li>
          <li><strong>Vary focal length and angle.</strong> Wide, medium, close-up. Static, panning, tracking. Same subject, different perspective.</li>
          <li><strong>Match motion between shots.</strong> Slow pan cuts to slow pan; fast zoom cuts to fast zoom. Mismatched motion feels like an error.</li>
          <li><strong>Cut on beat for short-form.</strong> Reels and TikTok reward rhythm — cuts every 1-3 seconds aligned to music beats.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep clips under 8 seconds.</strong> Longer clips stall momentum. Trim in the timeline, do not defend an "epic" shot.</li>
          <li><strong>Reinforce, do not distract.</strong> The b-roll should illustrate what is being said. Off-topic b-roll pulls attention away from the message.</li>
          <li><strong>Build a b-roll library.</strong> Every shoot should feed a reusable library of on-brand cutaways. It cuts future production time in half.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — reaching for stock footage</div>
          <p>Generic stock b-roll (aerial city shots, keyboard hands) feels lazy and dilutes brand recognition. It is better to shoot 30 seconds of real environment on a phone than to layer glossy stock into a founder video.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common b-roll mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Shooting only what fits the script.</strong> The script changes in the edit; shoot broadly.</li>
          <li><strong>Same focal length throughout.</strong> All medium shots read as monotone; vary wide, medium, close.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring audio in the b-roll.</strong> Ambient sound (typing, coffee shop, workshop noise) adds texture even when the A-roll audio dominates.</li>
          <li><strong>Overusing slow-motion.</strong> A little goes a long way; slow-mo on every clip looks like a music video.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the b-roll shot list.</strong> Plan the shots on paper before the shoot; ad-libbing on set leaves gaps.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is b-roll in simple terms?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
